    <text>
        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 118. <placeName type="townland">Monataggart</placeName> 
                    I</name>, Co. <placeName type="county">Cork</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=CO061-022002-"
                >CO061-022002-</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Long cist burial?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>Possible long cist grave <ref type="bibliog" target="#POW1997"
                                >(<bibl><author>Power</author> et al, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >164</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, which contained 'black earth and charcoal and
                        ... some pieces of an old crock' <ref target="#BRA1879"
                                >(<bibl><author>Brash</author>
                            <date when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >161</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. Also discovered at this site was a possible souterrain
                        containing three further ogham stones (Monataggart II-IV) (<ref
                            type="bibliog" target="#QUA1896"><bibl><author>Quarry</author> (<date
                                when="1896">1896</date>), <biblScope type="pp"
                        >382</biblScope></bibl></ref>)</p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p>Possible lintel stone of a long cist grave
                            (<ref target="#BRA1879"><bibl><author>
                            Brash</author><date>1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >161</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. <rs type="material"/>
                        <rs type="dimensions"> (<measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height"
                            >2.20</measure>m x <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width"
                                >0.43</measure>m x <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth"
                                >0.30</measure>m) (converted from <ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#MAC1945"><bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date>1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp">116</biblScope></bibl></ref>).</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p>Up on one angle. Letters from groups B and H are inverted. The extra space left between VEQREQ and MOQOI is also noteworthy (represented by 'vac.' below). This occassional use of space to seperate words in ogham (see also <ref
                        target="search.php?ciic=118"
                        >CIIC 215</ref> Whitefield I, Co. Kerry) is discussed by <ref
                        type="bibliog" target="#MOF2011"><bibl><author>Moffat</author> (<date
                            when="2011">2011</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >290</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. Also noted by <ref
                                    type="bibliog" target="#MOF2011"><bibl><author>Moffat</author> (<date
                                        when="2011">2011</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                            >287</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, is the noticable change in this inscription from 'larger and more broadly spaced scores' initially, to 'finer and more closely spaced scores at the top of the angle'. Presumably the 
                        carver realised he was running out of space on that angle and decided to make the remaining letters fit the space rather than continuing over the top of the stone.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <lb/>
                    <persName><w lemma="VEQREQ">
                       VEQREQ
                    </w></persName> <space></space>
                    <w type="formula" lemma="MUCOI">MOQOI</w>
                    <persName><w lemma="GLUNLEGGET">GLUNLEGGET</w></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <head>Translation</head>
                <p>
                    <q>of <persName>Fíachri</persName> descendant of Glún...?</q>
                </p>
            </div>
