            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>This is one of the inscriptions listed by <ref type="bibliog"
                        target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1945"
                            >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">96</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> in
                        which syncope (dropping of internal vowels) begins to show
                        itself (loss of vowel indicated by asterisk: VEQ*REQ, GLUN*LEGGET). 
                        Therefore, it may be dated to the 
                        <origDate notBefore="0570" notAfter="0630">late sixth or early seventh century</origDate> 
                        <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author> <date when="1945"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">97</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p><foreign xml:lang="ga">VEQREQ</foreign>: probably a compound of
                            *<hi rend="italic">veiko</hi> '<gloss>energetic, hostile</gloss>' + <hi rend="italic">rí</hi> '<gloss>king</gloss>'
                                (-<foreign>RIGAS</foreign> > <foreign>REG</foreign> >
                                <foreign>REC</foreign>). Although we would rather expect
                                <foreign>*VECREG</foreign> or later <foreign>*VECREC</foreign>,
                        Early Old Irish <foreign xml:lang="ga"><hi rend="italic">Fechrech</hi></foreign> (see <ref
                                type="bibliog" target="#MCM1986"><bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1986">1986</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >2-4</biblScope></bibl></ref>). The same symbol (Q) being used for both
                            guttural sounds is significant in that it shows that these sounds had
                            already fallen together <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991"
                                    >(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">116,
                                    12</biblScope></bibl>2)</ref>. <ref target="MCM1986"
                                    ><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date>1986</date>, <biblScope
                                    type="pp">pp 30-1</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, following <ref
                                type="bibliog" target="FER1879"><bibl><author>Ferguson</author> (<date
                                    when="1879">1879</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >207-10</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, suggests a possible reading CH (4 scores
                        for C and 1 for H) /<hi rend="italic">x</hi>/ rather than Q (5 scores).</p></item>
                    <item n="3"><p><foreign xml:lang="ga">MOQOI</foreign> for <foreign xml:lang="ga"
                        >MUCOI</foreign> (here velar sound /<hi rend="italic">k</hi>/).</p></item>
                    <item n="4"><p><foreign xml:lang="ga">GLUNLEGGET</foreign>: unidentified tribal
                        name (<foreign xml:lang="ga"><hi rend="italic">glún</hi></foreign> '<gloss>knee</gloss>'? and
                            ?).</p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Possibly used as lintel in possible long cist grave in townland of 
                                <placeName type="townland">Monataggart</placeName>, parish of
                                <placeName type="parish">Donoughmore</placeName>, barony of
                                <placeName type="barony">East Muskerry</placeName>. The original
                            location of this stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=CO061-022002-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS coordinates
                            <geo>-8.787796,51.976513</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Unknown</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation"><orgName>National Museum of Ireland</orgName> (<idno>NMI Ref. 1874:91</idno>), 
                            <placeName>Dublin</placeName>. The present location of
                            this stone may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=DU018-366-----"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS coordinates
                                <geo>-6.254558,53.340408</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p><q>found in <date when="1872">1872</date>, used as building material in the
                        construction of an underground chamber on this townland...the stone was
                        taken out by the farmer [<persName>Mr. <forename>Patrick</forename>
                            <surname>Cogan</surname></persName>], who made a gatepost of it -
                        drilling a hole through the top for this purpose. Covered with whitewash in
                        this service it was discovered by <name type="author">Brash</name>, who
                        brought it to notice</q>' <ref target="MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                        <date when="1945">1945</date>,<biblScope type="pp">pp 116,
                        118</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. </p>
            </div>
